This paper is likely to belong to the following arXiv CS sub-categories: 

1. cs.CL (Computation and Language): This paper focuses on spoken language processing, dialogue management, and language generation, which are all sub-fields of computational linguistics. 

2. cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence): The development of a social chatbot involves the use of artificial intelligence techniques such as natural language processing, machine learning, and dialogue management. 

3. cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction): The user-centric design of the chatbot and the insights gained from real-world user interactions suggest that this paper is relevant to the field of human-computer interaction. 

4. cs.SD (Sound): The use of spoken language processing and speech recognition technologies in the chatbot may make this paper relevant to the field of sound. 

5. cs.CY (Computers and Society): The social nature of the chatbot and its potential impact on society may make this paper relevant to the field of computers and society.
